body_text.text:
Certain RNA viruses can produce both homologous and nonhomologous RNA recombinants.
The molecular mechanism involved in the formation of homologous and nonhomologous recombinants was tested using an efficient recombination system of brome mosaic virus (BMV). A partially debilitating BMV RNA3 mutant was repaired in vivo by exchanges with the sequences of other BMV RNA components. Low recombination frequency was overcome by construction of RNA3-based recombination vectors, where recombinationally active sequences could be inserted and analyzed. It appeared that short base-paired regions between the two BMV RNA recombination substrates can target efficient nonhomologous recombination crossovers. A model invokes the formation of local RNA–RNA heteroduplexes to be responsible for targeting the RNA crossovers as a result of: (1) bringing the RNA substrates into a close proximity; and (2) slowing down or stalling the approaching replicase enzyme complex (Fig. 3
).
